text:
I don't know if anyone ever mentioned/ noticed this but did anyone see the young boy wearing hat from 1:46 (slow down the video on 0.1x speed). My take is that it was Scaramouche. 

I think it probably goes off like this. 

We know that Scaramouche has an alias that goes with "The Balladeer" and we know that Ei was the one who created him as a prototype vessel but later abandoned and instead was given some power from Ei herself. I suspect that this clone has no place for the current civilization in Inazuma back at the time (due to the lack of affiliations that he has with anyone) so he tried to find a place where everyone would accept him wholeheartedly. 

Feeling abandoned with hatred on his feeling (because Ei created him basically for nothing and held grudge against her), Scaramouche went to the southernmost island (the most exiled island of Inazuma) and met the tribe who worship the thunderbird instead of electro archon. He made a relationship with its people without telling about his origin and his affiliation with Ei as the electro archon.   

The people that worship the Thunderbird was quite delightful at first seeing how Scaramouche performed his ability as a balladeer (the same way Venti does to Mondstadt citizen, cheering them with joy via poem et cetera) and later on when the next ritual happened, Scaramouche began to sang his ballad and poems for the bird to show his appreciation. The thunderbird which didn't even care about the tribe began to show its liking at Scaramouche and demanded to see him again when the next ritual take place. 

The original tribe however began to envy how the thunderbird took a liking on Scaramouche despite him being the newcomer and began to exile him and assault him both physically and mentally. Scaramouche then living his day off as a loner again, being hated by the tribe who welcomed him at first. The last straw was the fact that they were going to took Scaramouche's life away as an offering.   

The Thunderbird then enraged and killed all of the tribe. The survivors who barely managed to escape from the massacre escaped to Inazuma from both Seirai and Tsurumi, seeking protection from electro archon, the same way that salt followers seeking protection on geo archon . Scaramouche, however, after seeing the massacre began to take all the blame and guilt on himself for his arrival that made the entire tribe killed. At the same time, he was blaming the thunderbird for massacring its follower because they did nothing wrong. Scaramouche thought that the reason its people became like that it's because of his arrival. 

He then left the Tsurumi island and met the Fatui. He later developed a mixed way of thinking that trusting people and making bonds with them is waste of time because they are going to use him anyway. After the tragedy and his meeting with fatui, he later claimed his self as "The Balladeer", the boy who was once known for his ability to cheer people and bring joy with poems and ballads, now singing his poem to bring agony and misery to people who hear his poetry. 

As for the thunderbird, he then exiled himself on the top of the Seirai island, filled with sorrows, regrets, and hatred for anyone who dares showed themselves upon them thanks to Scaramouche's departure from Tsurumi.

text:
Childe is an amazing character and I love how much screentime he gets. ^^
I mean he is literally the reason why I started to play Genshin. At first I was like "yeah, Genshin is kinda nice, but I'll not gonna play it". One evening my best friend streamed it in discord while he was playing the archon quest in Liyue. As I saw Childe in his stream I thought "hmm, this NPC looks cool" and later on I also thought "wow, he has such good manners and is so kind, sadly just an NPC". 
In this moment my best friend: "Btw, I would say that you really would like playing this character."
Me: "Wait a sec, this is a playable character?!"
My best friend: "Yes and another reason, that would support my thesis: He's a hydro character."
Me: "OMG, ok you got me. I have to have him!"
My best friend: "Then you should start playing Genshin immediately, he's the char of the special character banner and you can only get him for the next 3 weeks."

text: ¬†@Justin Y.¬† it's a gacha,  not an anime or a standalone RPG game. They need to keep the characters essentially the same, without big growth, because they sell them as-is. Example: Diluc growing as a character would be him letting go of grief and grudges and living as a happier man. But this would be too much change from the "brooding loner" archetype he's marketed as, and people who were initially attracted to this product would feel like they didn't get what they paid for if he suddenly changed his attitude. So, keeping characters in the same spot is very intentional.
